{"id":"2208.11497","submitter":"Hua-Shu Dou","authors":"Hua-Shu Dou","title":"No Existence and Smoothness of Solution of the Navier-Stokes Equation","comments":"12 pages; 5 figures","journal-ref":"Entropy, 2022, 24, 339","doi":"10.3390/e24030339","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn math.AP math.DS nlin.CD","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The Navier-Stokes equation can be written in a form of Poisson equation. For\nlaminar flow in a channel (plane Poiseuille flow), the Navier-Stokes equation\nhas a non-zero source term and a non-zero solution within the domain. For\ntransitional flow, the velocity profile is distorted, and an inflection point\nor kink appears on the velocity profile, at a sufficiently high Reynolds number\nand large disturbance. In the vicinity of the inflection point or kink on the\ndistorted velocity profile, we can always find a point where the source term is\nzero. At this point, the Poisson equation is singular, due to the zero source\nterm, and has no solution at this point due to singularity. It is concluded\nthat there exists no smooth and physically reasonable solutions of the\nNavier-Stokes equation for transitional flow and turbulence in the global\ndomain due to singularity.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 20 Aug 2022 22:36:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-08-25"}
